[[Islam]] is a minority religion in [[Burundi]] where approximately [[Religion in Burundi|90 percent of the national population are followers of Christianity]]. Between 2–5 percent of the population identifies as Muslim, according to a 2010 estimate by the [[United States Department of State]].<ref name="state2010">{{cite web|title=Burundi|work=International Religious Freedom Report 2010|publisher=United States Department of State|url=https://www.state.gov/j/drl/rls/irf/2010/148667.htm|date=17 November 2010|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> The [[Pew Research Centre]] estimated in 2010 that there were 230,000 Muslims in Burundi, equivalent to 2.8 percent of Burundi's 8.4 million inhabitants.<ref name=Pew>{{cite web|title=Religions in Burundi|url=http://www.globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/burundi/religious_demography#/?affiliations_religion_id=0&affiliations_year=2010|website=Pew-Templeton Global Religious Futures Project|publisher=Pew Research Centres|accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>

==Religion==
{{islam by country}}
===History===
Islam first arrived in Burundi from [[East Africa]]n coast as part of the [[Arab slave trade]] in the late 19th century.{{sfn|Luffin|1999|p=29}} The Arabs were prevented from entering the [[Kingdom of Burundi]] by a successful campaign of resistance led by ''[[mwami]]'' (king) [[Mwezi IV Gisabo of Burundi|Mwezi IV Gisabo]].{{sfn|Luffin|1999|p=29}} However, they did establish settlements at [[Ujiji]] and [[Uvira]] close to the country's current borders.{{sfn|Luffin|1999|p=29}} The number of Muslims in Burundi increased under [[German East Africa|German colonial rule]] (1894–1916) and the German administration favoured the use of [[Swahili language|Kiswahili]] which was widely associated with the country's Muslims. By the outbreak of [[World War I]], the capital [[Bujumbura]] (then Usumbura) was a majority Muslim city.{{sfn|Luffin|1999|p=29}} The religion declined under [[Ruanda-Urundi|Belgian colonial rule]] (1916–62) as a result of the spread of [[Catholicism]] and the migration of non-Muslim Burundians to the cities.{{sfn|Luffin|1999|p=29}}

===Today===
Today the Muslim population is strongly urbanised and focused in the cities of Bujumbura, especially in the [[Commune of Buyenzi|communes of Buyenzi]] and [[Commune of Bwiza|Bwiza]], as well as [[Gitega]], [[Rumonge]], [[Nyanza Lac|Nyanza]], [[Muyinga]], and [[Makamba, Burundi|Makamba]]. The great majority are [[Sunni]] while a small minority are [[Shia]] and [[Ibadi]].<ref name="state2010"/>{{sfn|Luffin|1999|p=29}} Most are Swahili speakers although they may speak other [[Languages of Burundi|national languages]].{{sfn|Luffin|1999|p=29}} A significant proportion of the Muslim community are recent immigrants to the country from [[West Africa]], the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], the [[Middle East]], and [[Pakistan]].{{sfn|Luffin|1999|p=29}} Native Burundian Muslims belong to both of the country's major ethnic groups ([[Hutu]] and [[Tutsi]]) and successfully managed to avoid become involved in the [[Burundian genocides]] and ethnic violence since independence.{{sfn|Luffin|1999|p=29}}

The Republic of Burundi is [[Religion in Burundi|officially secular]] but several Muslim festivals, including [[Eid ul-Fitr]] and [[Eid al-Adha]], are celebrated as [[Public holidays in Burundi|national holidays]] alongside Christian observances.<ref name="state2010"/> Despite being only a small proportion of the national population, Muslims are represented in senior positions in Burundian politics and society, especially since the end of the [[Burundian Civil War]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Despite small numbers, Burundi Muslims still influential|url=http://www.worldbulletin.net/news/159752/despite-small-numbers-burundi-muslims-still-influential|date=26 May 2015|publisher=World Bulletin|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref>

